<h1 class="hero-h">A 90-day AI implementation roadmap <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">that actually ships.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Most AI implementation roadmaps are vague. They list "adopt AI" as a milestone. This is a concrete 90-day template — week by week, owner by owner, deliverable by deliverable — built from the rollouts we have run at B2B companies between $5M and $50M.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">How to use this</span><h2 class="h2">Read this once, then customize</h2><p class="body">This template is opinionated. It assumes a B2B team of 10–50 people, a CEO or COO sponsor, and at least one operations person who can own the work. If you are bigger or more regulated, the timeline stretches; if you are smaller and faster, it compresses.</p><p class="body">Three rules before you start. (1) Pick one revenue function and one operations function — do not try to roll AI out everywhere. (2) Name a single human owner per workflow you change — no committees. (3) Define what "shipped" looks like for each phase before you start that phase.</p><div class="callout"><p>A 90-day roadmap fails the same way every time: leaders treat it as a slide deck instead of a calendar. Put every milestone in a real calendar with a named owner and a checkpoint date. Half of execution is just making the schedule visible.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Phase 1: Days 1-30</span><h2 class="h2">Foundations, audit, and one quick win</h2><h3 class="h3">Week 1 — Alignment</h3><ul class="ul"><li><strong>CEO statement of intent</strong> — one paragraph: what is the goal, who owns it, what is the budget envelope.</li><li><strong>Name the AI lead</strong> — one human, 8-12 hrs/week minimum. Not a committee.</li><li><strong>Inventory current AI usage</strong> — who is already using what (ChatGPT, Copilot, Claude, etc.), paid or shadow.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Week 2 — Audit</h3><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Map the 10 most time-consuming repeatable workflows</strong> across sales, marketing, ops, and admin.</li><li><strong>Rank them by leverage</strong>: time saved × frequency × confidence in AI fit.</li><li><strong>Pick the top 3</strong>. The rest go on the backlog.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Week 3 — Tool selection &amp; access</h3><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Decide on the LLM platform.</strong> For most teams: Claude Team for general business use; ChatGPT Team if your stack is already Microsoft-heavy.</li><li><strong>Provision seats</strong> for everyone in the affected workflows, not just the AI lead.</li><li><strong>Confirm data handling</strong>: which models train on your data (avoid them for client work), which do not.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Week 4 — One quick win shipped</h3><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Pick the smallest of your top 3 workflows.</strong> Build the Project, write the system prompt, train the one or two people who will use it daily.</li><li><strong>Ship it for real.</strong> Not a demo — actual production use.</li><li><strong>Phase 1 deliverable:</strong> one workflow visibly working, with measurable time saved.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Phase 2: Days 31-60</span><h2 class="h2">Ship the remaining two priority workflows</h2><h3 class="h3">Week 5-6 — Workflow #2</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Same loop: define workflow, build Project, write system prompt, train users, ship.</li><li>Add a <strong>weekly review</strong>: 30 minutes with the AI lead and the workflow owner to look at real outputs and refine.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Week 7-8 — Workflow #3</h3><ul class="ul"><li>By now the team has a pattern. Workflow #3 should ship faster than #1 did.</li><li>Document what you have learned about your team — what works, what fails, what people resist.</li></ul><div class="callout"><p>If you have not shipped any of your top 3 workflows by end of week 8, stop adding workflows. Diagnose why the first one stalled. Usually the answer is no named owner or no time carved out — both fixable, neither solved by adding scope.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Phase 3: Days 61-90</span><h2 class="h2">Scale, train, govern</h2><h3 class="h3">Week 9-10 — Adjacent workflows</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Each shipped workflow has neighbors. The proposal workflow has a follow-up email workflow. The content workflow has a distribution workflow. Pick 2-3 neighbors and ship them.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Week 11 — Training the rest of the team</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Hold a 90-minute internal training where the workflow owners demo what they built.</li><li>Publish a one-page AI Usage Policy: what is OK to put into AI tools, what is not, who to ask.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Week 12 — Review &amp; next quarter</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Review measured impact: hours saved, cycle time changes, output volume changes.</li><li>Set Q2 priorities: which 3 new workflows ship next, with which owners.</li><li><strong>Phase 3 deliverable:</strong> 5-7 workflows in production, a published policy, a named owner per workflow, and a Q2 backlog.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The owner checklist</span><h2 class="h2">Print this and tape it to the AI lead's wall</h2><ul class="checklist"><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Every workflow has a named human owner — not a committee, not a function.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Every workflow has a measurable outcome defined before work starts.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Every workflow has a weekly checkpoint with the AI lead in the first month.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>No workflow is launched without the people who will use it being trained on it.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>No workflow is left running without someone reviewing outputs monthly.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Every workflow has documented prompts, projects, and templates stored in a shared location.</span></li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">What this template does not cover</span><h2 class="h2">Where you will need help</h2><p class="body">Workflows that touch regulated data (HIPAA, SOC 2, financial advice) require an additional 30-45 days of compliance work. Add that to the front of the timeline if you are in those industries.</p><p class="body">Enterprise rollouts (200+ people) need a different model — federated by function with a small central enablement team. This template is for teams under 100.</p><p class="body">If you have never deployed software internally before, the change-management work is bigger than the AI work. Plan for that explicitly.</p></div></section>

